hypothesis.value:
It is well-established that individuals who are treated as experts in some fields, such as political judgement, are overconfident in their estimates of the probabilities of future events (Tetlock, 2005). In a set of exploratory analyses, we plan to collect preliminary/pilot evidence to estimate:

- the degree to which non-experts are over- or under-confident in the accuracy of their predictions concerning the number of people who will die of COVID-19 in their country by the end of the year, the number of people who are infected of COVID-19 in their country by the end of the year, the infection fatality rate worldwide by the end of the year, and the infection fatality rate in their country by the end of the year;

- to determine whether participants’ levels of pessimism, 75% confidence interval widths, and calibration scores (75% minus proportion answered correct) regarding deaths, infections, and infection fatality rates are predicted by participant numeracy, education level (university vs. no university), and status as a healthcare provider vs. non-healthcare provider.

